Rivers State Governor, Nyesom Ezenwo Wike led members of the State Taskforce on Enforcement of the Ban on Public and Religious Gatherings, to monitor compliance with the directive of the state government for all markets in the state to remain closed. The Rivers State government, through Executive Order signed by Wike on March 27, 2020 declared that all markets in the state no matter how small are to remain closed with effect from Saturday, March 28, 2020 to check the spread of coronavirus in the state. Members of the Task Force who accompanied Governor Wike on the monitoring exercise include: The Rivers State Police Commissioner,  the State Director of Department of State Services (DSS) and  the Commander, Nigeria Air Force, 115 Special Operations Group, Port Harcourt. Others were the Commander, Nigerian Navy Ship (NNS) Pathfinder and the State Commandant of the Nigeria Security and Civil Defence Corps (NSCDC). There was general compliance with the directive of the state government as the traders locked the markets and stayed away. The governor and other taskforce members monitored compliance at the popular Umbrella Market by the Rail track under Mile One Flyover,  the Mile One Market, the Mile Two Market, the Mile Three Market and the Mile Four Market. He led the team to also monitor compliance at the Rumuokwuta Market,  Rumuomasi Market , Elekahia Market,  Slaughter Market and the Creek Road Market. Wike, who stopped at the different markets interacted with security personnel and operatives of the State Taskforce on Street Trading and Illegal Motor Parks and issued relevant instructions.